english:
  title: Preface to the Farewell of the Venerable Water-Mirror
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When Confucius passed from the world, the Buddha-dharma emerged and stood in opposition to the Confucian way. Its teachings are ethereal and lofty, yet distant from the principles of the mundane world, and so those who champion the Confucian path have reviled it. None more vigorously than Han Yu of the Tang dynasty. Yet when one reads his writings, one often discovers passages where his spirit mingles with Buddhist sentiment, appearing frequently between his lines. Could it not be that these men possessed such clarity of spirit and purity of conduct, such indifference to glory and shame, such equanimity toward life and death, that they soared immeasurably beyond those enslaved by fear of loss and the mire of desire?

    I have recited their verses and read their books, and in doing so, glimpsed the nature of these souls. Now Venerable Sugyeong has shaved his head and from that moment onward never set foot upon the path of worldly ambition. He wanders among mountains and waters, serene in bearing, crystalline in speech. Though even Han Yu were reborn, he would surely not forsake his friendship. As for one as unworthy as myself, standing before such noble character, I only lament my late meeting with him. How then can I presume to judge?

    Alas, our acquaintance is but young, yet suddenly he departs for Yeongnam. And Yeongnam's landscape is supreme in all the Eastern lands, crowned by Mount Duryusan. Within Duryusan stands the Water-Mirror Temple, a great monastic hall. None but those versed in the Buddhist teachings and esteemed by the multitude could receive ordination there. This journey serves not merely to satisfy a refined love of mountain scenery, but truly marks the season when the Buddhist disciple may walk the Way with an open heart. Why should our petty sorrow at parting deserve a second glance? Thus we gathered in the eastern fields, distributed rhyme schemes, composed verses, and asked me to write this preface.
  footnotes:
    - Han Yu (韓愈), Tang dynasty official and writer, was famously critical of Buddhism despite his literary admiration for Buddhist monks
    - Duryusan (頭流山) is Mount Dureyu, a sacred mountain in Yeongnam (southern Korea), known for its natural beauty
    - Water-Mirror Temple (水精寺) refers to a major Buddhist monastery, a "great hall" (叢林) where serious practitioners gathered
